Mac-vlan and eye-p-vlan, real local-area-network addresses.

Mac-vlan gives a container its own distinct hardware address on the host's physical local-area network. To the rest of the network, the switches, routers, and address servers, the container looks like a completely separate machine with a real address, and there is no network address translation in the way. Eye-p-vlan is the close cousin that shares the host's hardware address and gives the container an address without a unique one of its own, which is useful when your switch rejects unfamiliar hardware addresses.

When would you actually want this. The honest answer is rarely, and only for specific cases. A containerised legacy app that needs to broadcast on the local-area network, using older discovery protocols, is one. Internet-of-things or home-automation bridges that must participate in local discovery are another. And network appliances like intrusion sensors or packet captures that need to see traffic in promiscuous mode are a third. For pretty much everything else, a plain bridge with a published port is simpler, more portable, and does not depend on the details of your physical network.

There is one surprising gotcha to flag. By default, the host itself cannot reach a mac-vlan container, because the kernel will not loop traffic back out through the parent interface and in again. The standard workaround is to create a matching sub-interface on the host as well and route through it. It is the kind of thing that catches everyone the first time, so it is worth knowing before you debug it from scratch.
